</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#D5D4D5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/uevesongbard.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Evesong Bard</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>l33t d00d!</span><br> <font color=#000033>(1/14/02 12:06:34 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/feqasylumbard.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=417.topic&index=30>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Crowd Control [Was: Twisting]</span><hr size=1> I love charming -- even with multiple adds, but I use it only on mobs that require more than a few seconds to kill.   If a mob dies consistantly before I can charm, sic pet and beat on target for more than a few seconds, I'll mez instead of charm. <br>
<br>
For a single add with a non-trivial mob:<br>
    Target pet<br>
    Charm<br>
    ASSIST<br>
    [Twist 3 songs of choice here]<br>
    Beat on mob until I _feel_ that charm is going to break<br>
    /pet target<br>
    rince, lather, repeat...<br>
<br>
For more than 2 adds, I usually don't fight -- I'm too busy keeping the mobs under control, but I will recruit one add to take my place.   Communication is crucial in this case, because worried group members may do  bad things to your pet if you don't tell them, such as slow, snare or root it.<br>
<br>
Also, I find charm absolutely shines when taking on really tough mobs.   Having an extra damage dealer in the group can turn the tide of a close battle.    In certain situations, I'll PULL a mob just so I can charm it just for this reason.<br>
<br>
For those desparate situations when we have one too many unmezzable/uncharmable adds (think Kael or DN), I'll take a chance with SoH.   I've had mixed results with it, but when it works it's a real lifesaver.<br>
<br>
