<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> BTW - I've also had great luck, and fun, using Highsun in places like Akheva on unmezzable mobs. Never once trained my group, and its an effective way to keep the mob off your chanter/slower/healer while you are dealing with the first unmezzable mob. Just sucks when its &quot;nighttime&quot;.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I've been playing with this song more lately, and have found it to be one of the more interesting songs in our lineup.   It seems to work best in zones where mobs have lazy aggro (e.g. when they get out of range, they don't bother coming back until you're close to them).  Outdoor zones seem to have this property more often than indoor zones.   I think Akheva is one of the rare exceptions -- when you run out of range of those Centis they tend to forget about you.<br>
<br>
I found another pretty neat use for this song: selective pulling.   This seems to work great in outdoor zones.   For example, in Maidens Eye,  if you know you have pulling duty and only those goranga scouts are up (3 by a rock, they always aggro together).   Sometimes lull works, but if it's resisted it tends to aggro all 3 of these tough mobs.    Instead of training them to zone, lead them well away from their spawnpoint then use song of highsun to send them back to their spawn point.<br>
<br>
Here's another technique that I find that's pretty neat.  If you have a single troublesome mob (such as those goranga hunters in maidens) among lots of manageable mobs,  what you can do is use this song to gate the troublesome mob back to his spawn point.   Then ZONE/camp to clear (lazy) aggro.   If you're lucky you're left with an area full of mobs that are easy to deal with before the troublesome mob wanders back.<br>
<br>
Thanks for getting me thinking about this song Joxur: I'd love to hear other uses for this great song.<br>
<br>
Evesong<br>
